│ "thoughts": "### 1. Understanding the Issue\n\nThe `ipsccp` pass incorrectly deduces    │
│ that an `alloca` instruction can have a constant pointer value. In the provided         │
│ reproducer, the pass analyzes a conditional branch: `br i1 %cmp, label %if, label       │
│ %exit`, where `%cmp` is `icmp eq ptr %a, inttoptr (i64 -1 to ptr)`. When considering    │
│ the `if` block (the true successor), `ipsccp` assumes that the condition `%cmp` must be │
│ true. It then incorrectly concludes that the value of `%a` (an `alloca`) must be        │
│ `inttoptr (i64 -1 to ptr)`. This faulty assumption leads to the replacement of `%a`     │
│ with this constant pointer inside the `if` block. Consequently, the                     │
│ `llvm.lifetime.start` intrinsic is called with an invalid argument, causing the         │
│ verifier to abort.\n\nThe core of the problem is that an `alloca`'s address is not a    │
│ compile-time constant and cannot be equal to an arbitrary integer-derived pointer. The  │
│ `icmp eq` comparison should always evaluate to `false`, and the `if` block should be    │
│ marked as unreachable.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe `opt` log clearly shows   │
│ the verifier failing with the error: `llvm.lifetime.start/end can only be used on       │
│ alloca or poison`. The invalid IR presented in the error message, `call void            │
│ @llvm.lifetime.start.p0(ptr inttoptr (i64 -1 to ptr))`, confirms that the `alloca` `%a` │
│ was replaced by a constant pointer. The backtrace points to the `VerifierPass` running  │
│ after `ipsccp`, which strongly indicates that `ipsccp` generated the malformed          │
│ IR.\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe root cause lies within the                     │
│ `SCCPInstVisitor::visitTerminator` function in                                          │
│ `llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/SCCPSolver.cpp`. This function is responsible for            │
│ propagating information along control flow edges. When it encounters a conditional      │
│ branch based on an `icmp` instruction, it calls `getPredicateInfoFor` to deduce facts   │
